<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate price per square meter?", answer: "Divide the total cost by the area in square meters. For example, if an apartment costs $300,000 and has an area of 85 m², the price per square meter is $300,000 / 85 = $3,529.41/m². This metric is the international standard for comparing property values and construction costs, used widely in Europe, Asia, Australia, and most countries outside the United States." },
  { question: "How do I convert price per sqm to price per sqft?", answer: "Divide the price per square meter by 10.7639 to get the price per square foot. Since 1 m² = 10.7639 sqft, a price of $3,000/m² equals $3,000 / 10.7639 = $278.71/sqft. Conversely, multiply price per sqft by 10.7639 to get price per m². This calculator handles both conversions automatically regardless of which unit you input." },
  { question: "What is a typical price per square meter for construction?", answer: "Construction costs per square meter vary enormously by location, building type, and finish quality. In the United States, residential construction typically ranges from $1,100 to $4,300/m² ($100 to $400/sqft). In Europe, costs range from EUR 1,000 to EUR 3,500/m². In developing countries, costs can be as low as $300 to $800/m². Commercial and industrial construction have their own ranges. Always compare within the same market and building type." },
  { question: "How do I calculate price per acre from price per square meter?", answer: "One acre equals 4,046.86 square meters. To get price per acre, multiply the price per square meter by 4,046.86. For example, if land costs $50/m², the price per acre is $50 x 4,046.86 = $202,343 per acre. This calculator computes price per acre automatically along with all other conversions." },
  { question: "Should I use price per sqm or price per sqft?", answer: "Use whichever unit is standard in your local market. Most countries use price per square meter (m²), while the United States, United Kingdom, and Canada commonly use price per square foot (sqft). When comparing properties across different countries or markets, convert everything to the same unit for meaningful comparison. This calculator shows both so you can work in either system." }
]) %>

